
======================================================================
1. SPECTRAL DATA RECAP
======================================================================

Tournament polynomial: z²-5z+6 = (z-2)(z-3)
  Roots: [2, 3]

Petersen adjacency spectrum:
  λ = +3, multiplicity = 1
  λ = +1, multiplicity = 5
  λ = -2, multiplicity = 4

======================================================================
2. TOURNAMENT POLYNOMIAL AT PETERSEN EIGENVALUES
======================================================================

f(z) = z²-5z+6 evaluated at Petersen eigenvalues:
  f(+3) =    0  (mult=1, contribution = 0)
  f(+1) =    2  (mult=5, contribution = 10)
  f(-2) =   20  (mult=4, contribution = 80)

  Tr(f(A_P)) = Σ mult·f(λ) = 90
  = f(3)·1 + f(1)·5 + f(-2)·4
  = 0 + 10 + 80
  = 0 + 10 + 80 = 90

  Note: f(3)=0 because 3=KEY₂ is a root!
  So the dominant eigenvalue contributes NOTHING.
  The trace is entirely from the 'error' eigenvalues.

======================================================================
3. PETERSEN MINIMAL POLY AT TOURNAMENT ROOTS
======================================================================

p(z) = z³-2z²-5z+6 evaluated at tournament polynomial roots:
  p(KEY₁) = p(2) = -4
  p(KEY₂) = p(3) = 0
  p(KEY₁+KEY₂) = p(5) = 56
  p(KEY₁·KEY₂) = p(6) = 120

  p(2) = 8-8-10+6 = -4
  p(3) = 27-18-15+6 = 0
  p(2) = -4 ← NEGATIVE! (2 is between roots 1 and 3)
  p(3) = 0 ← ZERO! (3 IS a root)

The shared root 3 = KEY₂ is the bridge between the two polynomials.
  gcd of z²-5z+6 and z³-2z²-5z+6:
  z²-5z+6 = (z-2)(z-3)
  z³-2z²-5z+6 = (z-3)(z-1)(z+2)
  GCD = (z-3)

======================================================================
4. COMPOSITION OF POLYNOMIALS
======================================================================

What is f(p(z))? Tournament polynomial composed with Petersen:
  f(p(z)) = p(z)² - 5·p(z) + 6
  = [p(z) - 2][p(z) - 3]
  = [z³-2z²-5z+4][z³-2z²-5z+3]

  f(p(z)) at small integers:
    z=-3: p(z)=   -24, f(p(z))=       702
    z=-2: p(z)=     0, f(p(z))=         6
    z=-1: p(z)=     8, f(p(z))=        30
    z=+0: p(z)=     6, f(p(z))=        12
    z=+1: p(z)=     0, f(p(z))=         6
    z=+2: p(z)=    -4, f(p(z))=        42
    z=+3: p(z)=     0, f(p(z))=         6
    z=+4: p(z)=    18, f(p(z))=       240
    z=+5: p(z)=    56, f(p(z))=      2862

  Roots of f(p(z)) = 0: p(z) = 2 or p(z) = 3
  p(z) = 2: z³-2z²-5z+4 = 0
  p(z) = 3: z³-2z²-5z+3 = 0 → (z-3)(z-1)(z+1) = 0? No...

  Roots of p(z)=2: [-1.85577251  0.67836283  3.17740968]
  Roots of p(z)=3: [-1.77338741  0.51996937  3.25341804]

  What about p(f(z))? Petersen composed with tournament:
  p(f(z)) = f(z)³ - 2f(z)² - 5f(z) + 6
  = [f(z)-3][f(z)-1][f(z)+2]
  = [(z-2)(z-3)-3][(z-2)(z-3)-1][(z-2)(z-3)+2]
    z=-3: f(z)=  30, p(f(z))=          25056
    z=-2: f(z)=  20, p(f(z))=           7106
    z=-1: f(z)=  12, p(f(z))=           1386
    z=+0: f(z)=   6, p(f(z))=            120
    z=+1: f(z)=   2, p(f(z))=             -4
    z=+2: f(z)=   0, p(f(z))=              6
    z=+3: f(z)=   0, p(f(z))=              6
    z=+4: f(z)=   2, p(f(z))=             -4
    z=+5: f(z)=   6, p(f(z))=            120
    z=+6: f(z)=  12, p(f(z))=           1386
    z=+7: f(z)=  20, p(f(z))=           7106

======================================================================
5. SPECTRAL ZETA FUNCTIONS
======================================================================

The spectral zeta function: ζ_G(s) = Σ |λ_i|^{-s}
(only meaningful for non-zero eigenvalues)

Petersen spectral zeta (with signs):
  ζ_P(1) = 1/3^1 + 5 + 4·(-2)^{-1} = 3.333333  (= 10/3)
  ζ_P(2) = 1/3^2 + 5 + 4·(-2)^{-2} = 6.111111  (= 55/9)
  ζ_P(3) = 1/3^3 + 5 + 4·(-2)^{-3} = 4.537037  (= 245/54)
  ζ_P(4) = 1/3^4 + 5 + 4·(-2)^{-4} = 5.262346  (= 1705/324)
  ζ_P(5) = 1/3^5 + 5 + 4·(-2)^{-5} = 4.879115  (= 9485/1944)
  ζ_P(6) = 1/3^6 + 5 + 4·(-2)^{-6} = 5.063872  (= 59065/11664)

Petersen heat kernel trace: Tr(e^{-tA}) = Σ mult·e^{-t·λ}
  = e^{-3t} + 5·e^{-t} + 4·e^{2t}
  t=0.1: Tr = 10.150616
  t=0.5: Tr = 14.128911
  t=1.0: Tr = 31.445409
  t=2.0: Tr = 219.071755

At t=0: Tr = 1+5+4 = 10 = |V(Petersen)| ✓
As t→∞: dominated by 4·e^{2t} (the -2 eigenvalue)

======================================================================
6. KRONECKER PRODUCT OF SPECTRA
======================================================================

Kronecker product T ⊗ P (treat tournament as 2×2 matrix with eigenvalues 2,3):

Eigenvalues of Kronecker product = all products λ_T × λ_P:
  2·+3 = +6  (mult=1)
  2·+1 = +2  (mult=5)
  2·-2 = -4  (mult=4)
  3·+3 = +9  (mult=1)
  3·+1 = +3  (mult=5)
  3·-2 = -6  (mult=4)

Distinct eigenvalues of T⊗P:
  λ = -6, total multiplicity = 4
  λ = -4, total multiplicity = 4
  λ = +2, total multiplicity = 5
  λ = +3, total multiplicity = 5
  λ = +6, total multiplicity = 1
  λ = +9, total multiplicity = 1

Trace of T⊗P = Σ mult·λ = 0
  = Tr(T)·Tr(P) = (2+3)·(3+5-8) = 5·0 = 0... 
  Wait: Tr(P) = 3·1 + 1·5 + (-2)·4 = 3+5-8 = 0
  So Tr(T⊗P) = Tr(T)·Tr(P) = 5·0 = 0 ✓

======================================================================
7. RAMANUJAN PROPERTY
======================================================================

A k-regular graph is Ramanujan if all non-trivial eigenvalues satisfy
|λ| ≤ 2√(k-1).

Petersen: k=3, so bound = 2√2 ≈ 2.8284
  Non-trivial eigenvalues: 1, -2
  |1| = 1 ≤ 2.8284 ✓
  |-2| = 2 ≤ 2.8284 ✓
  Petersen IS Ramanujan!

The Ramanujan bound for k-regular graphs:
  k= 2: 2√(k-1) = 2√1 = 2.0000
  k= 3: 2√(k-1) = 2√2 = 2.8284
  k= 4: 2√(k-1) = 2√3 = 3.4641
  k= 5: 2√(k-1) = 2√4 = 4.0000
  k= 6: 2√(k-1) = 2√5 = 4.4721
  k= 7: 2√(k-1) = 2√6 = 4.8990
  k= 8: 2√(k-1) = 2√7 = 5.2915
  k= 9: 2√(k-1) = 2√8 = 5.6569
  k=10: 2√(k-1) = 2√9 = 6.0000
  k=11: 2√(k-1) = 2√10 = 6.3246

The spectral gap of Petersen: λ₁ - λ₂ = 3 - 1 = 2 = KEY₁
For a 3-regular Ramanujan graph, the BEST possible gap is 3 - 2√2 ≈ 0.17
Petersen has gap 2, far exceeding the Ramanujan minimum.
In fact, gap = KEY₁ and max eigenvalue = KEY₂.

======================================================================
8. THE IHARA ZETA FUNCTION
======================================================================

The Ihara zeta function of a regular graph relates to the adjacency spectrum.

For a q+1 regular graph G with adjacency eigenvalues λ_1,...,λ_n:
  ζ_G(u)^{-1} = (1-u²)^{(q-1)n/2} · Π_i (1 - λ_i u + q u²)

For Petersen (3-regular, so q=2):
  ζ_P(u)^{-1} = (1-u²)^5 · (1-3u+2u²)(1-u+2u²)^5(1+2u+2u²)^4

Individual factors (1 - λu + 2u²):
  λ=+3: 1 - (3)u + 2u² = 2u² -3u + 1  (disc=1)
    Roots: u = 1.0000, 0.5000
  λ=+1: 1 - (1)u + 2u² = 2u² -1u + 1  (disc=-7)
    Roots: u = 0.2500 ± 0.6614i  (complex, |u| = 0.7071)
    |u|² = 1/q = 1/2 ← ON THE RAMANUJAN CIRCLE!
  λ=-2: 1 - (-2)u + 2u² = 2u² +2u + 1  (disc=-4)
    Roots: u = -0.5000 ± 0.5000i  (complex, |u| = 0.7071)
    |u|² = 1/q = 1/2 ← ON THE RAMANUJAN CIRCLE!

For Ramanujan graphs, all non-trivial zeros lie on |u| = q^{-1/2} = 1/√2
  1/√2 = 0.707107
  = 1/√KEY₁ = √(1/KEY₁)

This is the graph-theoretic analogue of the Riemann Hypothesis!
The Petersen graph satisfies this GRH analog, as expected for Ramanujan graphs.

