  All diagonal = 9 = f(0)+d = 6+3... 
  Actually: (A²)_{ii} = degree = 3, A_{ii} = 0
  f(A)_{ii} = 3 - 0 + 6 = 9 = KEY₂² ✓

  Off-diagonal: check (i,j) adjacent vs non-adjacent:
  f(A) when i~j: -5
  f(A) when i not~j: 1
  (checking another non-adj pair: f(A)_03 = 1)

  BEAUTIFUL STRUCTURE:
  f(A)_{i,i} = 9 = KEY₂²
  f(A)_{i,j} = -5 = -(KEY₁+KEY₂) when i~j
  f(A)_{i,j} = 1 = 1 when i≁j

  f(A) = 9I - 5A + (J-I-A)... wait
  f(A) = A² - 5A + 6I
  For Petersen (strongly regular (10,3,0,1)): A² = 3I + 0·A + 1·(J-I-A)
  A² = 3I + J - I - A = 2I - A + J
  f(A) = (2I - A + J) - 5A + 6I = 8I - 6A + J
  = rank(E₈)·I - h(G₂)·A + J
  = 8I - 6A + J

  Verify: 8I-6A+J has eigenvalues:
  On all-1 vector: 8-6·3+10 = 8-18+10 = 0 ✓ (matches f(3)=0)
  On 1-eigenvectors: 8-6·1+0 = 2 ✓ (matches f(1)=2)
  On (-2)-eigenvectors: 8-6·(-2)+0 = 20 ✓ (matches f(-2)=20)

  *** f(A_Petersen) = rank(E₈)·I - h(G₂)·A + J ***
  The tournament polynomial of the Petersen adjacency decomposes into
  exactly three Lie-meaningful terms!

======================================================================
GRAND SYNTHESIS: SPECTRAL COMPOSITION
======================================================================

1. f(A_P) = 8I - 6A + J = rank(E₈)·I - h(G₂)·A + J
2. The null space of f(A_P) is the all-1 eigenspace (graph regularity)
3. Petersen IS Ramanujan: Ihara zeros on |u|=1/√2=1/√KEY₁
4. The spectral gap of Petersen = KEY₁ = 2
5. Tr(f(A_P)) = 90 = 9·10 = KEY₂²·V(Petersen)
6. The tournament polynomial at Petersen eigenvalues: f(3)=0, f(1)=2, f(-2)=20
7. The shared root KEY₂=3 is the bridge: gcd(f,p) = (z-3)
